across all tests using the non-transformed, skewed phenotypes, from 7.5 to 20.1{\%} after Winsorizing and from 12.6 to 33.2{\%} after Box-Cox transformation. Likewise, power (adjusted for empirical type 1 error) using leptokurtic phenotypes at the 0.01 alpha level ranged from 4.4 to 12.5{\%} across all tests with no transformation, from 7 to 19.2{\%} after Winsorizing and from 4.5 to 13.8{\%} after Box-Cox transformation. Thus the Box-Cox transformation apparently provided the best type 1 error control and maximal power among the procedures we considered for analyzing a non-normal, skewed distribution (chi2) while Winzorizing worked best for the non-normal, kurtic distribution (Laplace). We repeated the same simulations using a larger sample size (200 sib pairs) and found similar results.},
